<paragraph blockId="19.[151,705,1052,1111]" box="[151,443,1086,1111]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<figureCitation box="[151,314,1086,1111]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 12–13" captionStart-1="FIGURE 14" captionStartId-0="55.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionStartId-1="56.[151,249,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox-0="[206,1387,181,1966]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetId-0="figure-34@55.[206,1387,181,1966]" captionTargetId-1="figure-44@56.[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetPageId-0="55" captionTargetPageId-1="56" captionText-0="FIGURES 12–13. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n., male: 12—habitus, left lateral; 13—habitus, dorsal." captionText-1="FIGURE 14. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n., male terminalia. Abbreviations: CER = cercus, PG = postgonite, SEM = emargination of sternite 5." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909067" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909069" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4909067/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4909069/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figures 12–14</figureCitation>
, and 86–96
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1158,2011]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,291,1158,1183]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description.</emphasis>
Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[464,677,1158,1183]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–13" captionStartId="55.[151,264,1984,2007]" captionTargetBox="[206,1387,181,1966]" captionTargetId="figure-34@55.[206,1387,181,1966]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURES 12–13. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n., male: 12—habitus, left lateral; 13—habitus, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909067/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figures 12 and 13</figureCitation>
. Body length 
<quantity box="[842,983,1158,1183]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.9">0.9–1.1 mm</quantity>
. Head ground color light brown. Frons finely rugose; pale areas silvery; dark brown medial stripes each about one-fourth the width of frons, narrowing toward the anterior margin then diffusing; dark brown orbital stripes each one-third the width of medial stripe; ocular emargination with silvery-white spot. Ocellar tubercle slightly raised, orange; ocelli present; ocellar bristle two-fifths the length of frons. Orbital bristle present; orbital setulae minute, in three pairs. Interfrontal setae in two pairs. Lunule with silvery-white spot; face shining; facial excavation with a silvery-white band continuing through ocular margin of gena; clypeus dark brown; gena brown but appearing dark brown from the front, weakly shining, setaceous. Antenna brown. Scutum and scutellum red-orange, shining. Scutum uniformly setose. Scutellum darker, bare; flat, 2.5 times wider than long, 0.6 times the width of scutum. Apical scutellar bristles twice as long as basal. Pleuron orange. Legs orange; fore femur, tibiae, and tarsi darker; mid tibia with two anterodorsal bristles, in male with row of six stout peg-like setae in ventrodistal third (compare to 
<figureCitation box="[919,1045,1518,1543]" captionStart="FIGURES 156–160" captionStartId="110.[151,264,1287,1310]" captionTargetBox="[407,1183,198,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-57@110.[393,1194,193,1266]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="FIGURES 156–160. Aptilotella involucris Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 156—female terminalia, dorsal; 157—female terminalia, left lateral; 158—female terminalia, ventral; 159—spermathecae; 160—male mid trochanter, femur and tibia, anterior. Abbreviations: EP = epiproct, HP = hypoproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909231/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 160</figureCitation>
). Wing rudiment brown. Abdomen black, shining; tergites each with two rows of long setae; sternites finely microtrichose. Epandrium and synsternite 6+7 dark reddish-brown; cercus and surstylus dull yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1158,2011]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1436,151,1149]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,392,1626,1651]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Male terminalia.</emphasis>
Sternite 5 (
<figureCitation box="[526,620,1626,1651]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="56.[151,249,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-44@56.[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 14. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n., male terminalia. Abbreviations: CER = cercus, PG = postgonite, SEM = emargination of sternite 5." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909069/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs. 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[633,662,1626,1651]" captionStart="FIGURES 86–89" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1106,1129]" captionTargetBox="[399,1191,199,1079]" captionTargetId="figure-42@93.[389,1198,193,1085]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 86–89. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 86—male terminalia, posterior; 87—male terminalia, left lateral; 88—male synsternite 6+7; 89—male sternite 5." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909193/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">89</figureCitation>
) deeply emarginate in posteromedial seventh and lined by two rows of thick setae. Synsternite 6+7 (
<figureCitation box="[510,592,1662,1687]" captionStart="FIGURES 86–89" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1106,1129]" captionTargetBox="[399,1191,199,1079]" captionTargetId="figure-42@93.[389,1198,193,1085]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 86–89. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 86—male terminalia, posterior; 87—male terminalia, left lateral; 88—male synsternite 6+7; 89—male sternite 5." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909193/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 88</figureCitation>
) with slightly arched medial bridge, giving rise to a pair of small sclerites. Cercus (
<figureCitation box="[243,336,1698,1723]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="56.[151,249,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-44@56.[151,1436,193,1478]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 14. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n., male terminalia. Abbreviations: CER = cercus, PG = postgonite, SEM = emargination of sternite 5." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909069" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909069/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs. 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[348,418,1698,1723]" captionStart="FIGURES 86–89" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1106,1129]" captionTargetBox="[399,1191,199,1079]" captionTargetId="figure-42@93.[389,1198,193,1085]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 86–89. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 86—male terminalia, posterior; 87—male terminalia, left lateral; 88—male synsternite 6+7; 89—male sternite 5." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909193/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">86, 87</figureCitation>
) compressed, four times as long as basal width; base setulose, lateral margin carinate; apex rounded, with two sensory setae; margin at midlength with one long seta and an adjacent sensory seta, and two setae in distal quarter. Surstylus (
<figureCitation box="[530,668,1770,1795]" captionStart="FIGURES 86–89" captionStartId="93.[151,264,1106,1129]" captionTargetBox="[399,1191,199,1079]" captionTargetId="figure-42@93.[389,1198,193,1085]" captionTargetPageId="93" captionText="FIGURES 86–89. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 86—male terminalia, posterior; 87—male terminalia, left lateral; 88—male synsternite 6+7; 89—male sternite 5." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909193" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909193/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs. 86, 87</figureCitation>
) saddle-shaped; posteroventral ridge bearing long setae. Postgonite (
<figureCitation box="[159,241,1806,1831]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–92" captionStartId="94.[151,264,1122,1145]" captionTargetBox="[469,1115,197,1097]" captionTargetId="figure-72@94.[462,1125,193,1101]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="FIGURES 90–92. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 90—aedeagus with postgonites removed; 91—left postgonite; 92—hypandrium. Abbreviations: BP = basiphallus, DTP = descending tab of paired arched sclerites, LFS = lateral flanking sclerite, PAS = paired arched sclerites, PTL = paired triangular lobes of paired arched sclerites, VBS = ventrobasal sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909195/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 91</figureCitation>
) broad; descending arm very short and curved forward, with two inner sensory setae; articulatory process for pregonite undeveloped, angular; articulatory process for basiphallus knobbed. Hypandrium (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1345,1842,1867]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–92" captionStartId="94.[151,264,1122,1145]" captionTargetBox="[469,1115,197,1097]" captionTargetId="figure-72@94.[462,1125,193,1101]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="FIGURES 90–92. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 90—aedeagus with postgonites removed; 91—left postgonite; 92—hypandrium. Abbreviations: BP = basiphallus, DTP = descending tab of paired arched sclerites, LFS = lateral flanking sclerite, PAS = paired arched sclerites, PTL = paired triangular lobes of paired arched sclerites, VBS = ventrobasal sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909195/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
) broad; medial rod apically dilated to the right, basal margin dilated; hypandrial arms slender; posteromedial fork and pregonite inconspicuous. Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[618,730,1914,1939]" captionStart="FIGURES 90–92" captionStartId="94.[151,264,1122,1145]" captionTargetBox="[469,1115,197,1097]" captionTargetId="figure-72@94.[462,1125,193,1101]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="FIGURES 90–92. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 90—aedeagus with postgonites removed; 91—left postgonite; 92—hypandrium. Abbreviations: BP = basiphallus, DTP = descending tab of paired arched sclerites, LFS = lateral flanking sclerite, PAS = paired arched sclerites, PTL = paired triangular lobes of paired arched sclerites, VBS = ventrobasal sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909195" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909195/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 90</figureCitation>
. Basiphallus stout, cylindrical; anterior margin weakly arched; posterodorsally with a truncate tubercle; articulatory process for postgonite truncate, curved upward. Ejaculatory apodeme columnar, appearing spongy and borne on a disc with four sensory pores. Ventrobasal sclerite divided. Lateral flanking sclerite broadly fused posteriorly, with a broad, curved descending tab; deeply indented at level of basiphallus; fused dorsally until halfway, where it darkens laterally, then dilates and descends, initially nearly converging, then twisting outward and tapering to a point. Paired arched sclerites very dark, originating at descending tab of lateral flanking sclerite; their trunks basally with an interior protuberance and a large, finelypointed and convergent triangular outer lobe; ascending and barely entering lateral flanking sclerites before descending again, becoming depressed and merging into a sickle-shaped, twice laterally frilled portion, which gently curves up between the apices of lateral flanking sclerites. Distal dorsal sclerite broad, originating at dorsal division of lateral flanking sclerite; dorsal surface dark and gradually curved; lateral margins straight; distally split into two divergent, upwardly curved lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,420,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Female terminalia.</emphasis>
Epiproct (
<figureCitation box="[539,673,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 93–96" captionStartId="95.[151,264,1181,1204]" captionTargetBox="[409,1175,193,1156]" captionTargetId="figure-47@95.[403,1185,193,1160]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 93–96. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 93—female terminalia, dorsal; 94—female terminalia, left lateral; 95—female terminalia, ventral; 96—spermathecae. Abbreviations: EP = epiproct, HP = hypoproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909197/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs. 93, 94</figureCitation>
) triangular, apically rounded and microtrichose. Each half of tergite 8 (
<figureCitation box="[184,322,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 93–96" captionStartId="95.[151,264,1181,1204]" captionTargetBox="[409,1175,193,1156]" captionTargetId="figure-47@95.[403,1185,193,1160]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 93–96. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 93—female terminalia, dorsal; 94—female terminalia, left lateral; 95—female terminalia, ventral; 96—spermathecae. Abbreviations: EP = epiproct, HP = hypoproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909197/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs. 93–95</figureCitation>
) convex; margin rounded; sparsely setaceous. Cercus three times as long as wide; with several scattered setae. Hypoproct (
<figureCitation box="[471,611,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 93–96" captionStartId="95.[151,264,1181,1204]" captionTargetBox="[409,1175,193,1156]" captionTargetId="figure-47@95.[403,1185,193,1160]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 93–96. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 93—female terminalia, dorsal; 94—female terminalia, left lateral; 95—female terminalia, ventral; 96—spermathecae. Abbreviations: EP = epiproct, HP = hypoproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909197/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs. 94, 95</figureCitation>
) reduced to a pair of curved, convergent rods; apically with a patch of microtrichosity and two pairs of setae. Spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[791,877,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURES 93–96" captionStartId="95.[151,264,1181,1204]" captionTargetBox="[409,1175,193,1156]" captionTargetId="figure-47@95.[403,1185,193,1160]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="FIGURES 93–96. Aptilotella pyropanda Luk &amp; Marshall, sp. n.: 93—female terminalia, dorsal; 94—female terminalia, left lateral; 95—female terminalia, ventral; 96—spermathecae. Abbreviations: EP = epiproct, HP = hypoproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909197" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909197/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 96</figureCitation>
) simple; sclerotized ducts long, three times the diameter of a spermatheca.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet is derived from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[865,926,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">pyros</emphasis>
, “fire,” and Latin 
<emphasis box="[1137,1218,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">pandus</emphasis>
, “bent, curved,” in reference to the fiery colour of the thorax, and the paired arched sclerites of the distiphallus, a defining character of this species and its relatives.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
