</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[335,580,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyropanda">
<emphasis box="[335,580,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Aptilotella pyropanda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily recognized by the fiery orange thorax and legs. In dorsal view, the highly reflective silvery-white spots of the ocular emarginations and lunule give the fly an appearance of having three “headlights.” This species has a relatively broad range with at least two populations along the Sierra Madre de Chiapas Mountains, one in the extreme Mexican southeast and the other in western 
<collectingCountry box="[1089,1214,1124,1149]" name="Guatemala" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
